00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:57.100
So let's move on.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:59.600
So -- so let's talk a
little bit about radio.

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.120
So now we'll start going back in time.

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:02.890
And, you know,
you can look at -- there's a

00:04:02.890 --> 00:04:05.140
definition of this that says
it's a way to -- to broadcast

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:07.270
information by electronic means.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.140
Well, Internet radio would fit
into that definition.

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:11.040
And it's really an old technology.

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:12.220
It's been around for 100 years.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:15.240
And, you know,
it's all based on through-the-air

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:16.940
-- radio frequency spectrum.

00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:21.040
And basically, originally,
there were -- there was actual data sent,

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:22.580
Morse code, you know, dots and dashes.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:23.730
Have you watched Titanic, right?

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:26.430
They were sending their -- their
messages with Morse code on radio,

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:29.680
and that was really just about maybe
10 years after radio existed that they

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:31.530
had that ability to do that on ships.

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.440
And then from the 1920s,
it really blossomed because they

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:36.480
had the ability to do voice.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:39.660
And, you know,
things got pretty interesting.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:44.340
So if you all look at this -- ooh,
this slide changed from

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:45.180
when I gave it to people.

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.160
That's exciting.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:51.760
You see about 1901,
Italian gentleman named Marconi went off

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:53.860
and did a first transatlantic signal.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:57.580
And then you see in the '20s,
he started commercial broadcasting.

00:04:57.580 --> 00:05:00.770
And then radio at home, you know,
Amos and Andy and all those old shows,

00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:03.560
the Green Hornet, you know,
people would -- during the Depression,

00:05:03.570 --> 00:05:05.360
didn't go out much and
radios were inexpensive.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.840
So that really became -- it was
what pretty much television is now,

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:10.900
but obviously television
hadn't existed yet.

00:05:10.900 --> 00:05:14.420
If you go back -- you go
further ahead in time,

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.990
about the 1960s,
there were other forms of

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:18.340
media competing with it,
television.

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:21.820
So, you know, radio changed as well,
and you get the better quality of FM.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:24.920
And then in the 1970s,
we had the first satellite networks.

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:28.440
And I'm not talking about like
XM or Sirius where you listen

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:29.720
-- you listen from a satellite.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:33.540
I'm talking about using satellites to
distribute programs around the world,

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:34.570
to affiliate stations.

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:37.680
So imagine if you're listening to a
nationally broadcast baseball game,

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.820
that's most likely coming over a
satellite into a radio station.

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:42.960
That all originated back in the '70s.

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:46.340
And then in the 1980s,
there was actually low-speed data that

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:48.940
was sent along with radio signals.

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:50.600
And there were these proprietary devices.

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:52.340
You get stock quotes and weather.

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:54.740
And, you know,
that kind of pre-sages things you

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:57.570
can do with internet radio and things
you can do with paging networks,

00:05:57.570 --> 00:05:58.240
et cetera.

00:05:58.330 --> 00:05:59.660
That's where all that started.

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:01.970
And then the 1990s,
talk a little bit about

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:03.520
the business side.

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:07.120
They changed the laws about how many
stations a single owner could have.

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:08.840
So you suddenly had these
huge groups coming out,

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:11.140
like Clear Channel,
Infinity Broadcasting,

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:14.880
where there are hundreds and thousands of
stations that are owned by one company.

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:16.590
And that changed the flavor of radio.

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:20.060
Radio maybe before those days
was very individual to a city.

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:22.780
And now there's a little bit
more of a homogenization.

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:25.610
So it's kind of -- it's, you know,
some people like it.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:27.560
Some people, you know,
don't understand that it's -- it

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:28.800
isn't different in every city.

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:30.490
But some people don't like it.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:33.520
And then, of course,
talk about the later '90s, we start,

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:35.520
you know,
we start talking about convergence.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:38.330
And when I -- I remember when I would
go to the National Association of

00:06:38.330 --> 00:06:40.660
Broadcasters show,
in the mid '90s, they were all saying,

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:42.550
"You know, radio is going to get
run over by convergence.

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:46.890
Convergence is really about -- about
video." And funny how radio seems to

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.700
have done pretty well at surviving this
and found its way into other mediums.

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:53.280
And it translated very nicely to it.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:56.580
So you want to broadcast.

00:06:56.650 --> 00:06:59.580
So it's very expensive to
do traditional broadcasts.

00:06:59.580 --> 00:06:59.880
Why?

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:03.500
Because it's based on nature
provides radio spectrum.

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:04.920
And there's a limited amount of that.

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:08.600
And there's regulations for, you know,
how stations can be organized in

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.380
a certain city so that otherwise
they interfere with each other.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:12.280
And that's all done by the U.S.

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:14.640
government,
the Federal Communications Commission.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:17.340
And they actually came up with
the rules for all this back in,

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:18.060
really, the '20s.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:19.500
And they did treaties
with other countries.

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:22.390
So if you ever go to Canada,
you see a lot of radio

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:23.380
stations along the border.

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:26.020
They have to send their signal
way up into Canada so they

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:27.230
don't interfere with U.S.

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:28.820
stations and vice versa.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:31.860
So there's a lot of things that
go on that you don't know about,

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:33.470
you know, with radio.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:35.480
And you have to have a regulatory body.

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:38.430
And you have to apply for a
license to be able to broadcast.

00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:41.950
There's not a cost to it,
but you have to prove that you're

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:43.480
doing things in the public good.

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:45.480
And there's a lot of
competition for them.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.480
And once a station gets a license,
it's very hard for them to lose it

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:51.400
unless they've broken a law or whatever.

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:54.450
And that's, you know,
that's limited by spectrum.

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:56.650
So if you want to go buy
or build a station in,

00:07:56.700 --> 00:08:00.480
let's say, a market like San Francisco,
you're talking maybe $50, 100 million,

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:03.460
which is, you know, not a small change.

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:05.370
But if you're talking
about a smaller market,

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:08.460
let's say, name a town out in, you know,
the middle of California,

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:12.460
you're talking maybe millions
for a small AM or FM station.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.860
So now recently, in the last five years,
we have satellite radio.

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:18.080
We talked about the different
kind of satellite distribution.

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:20.830
This is actually,
I'm talking about Sirius and XM and

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:23.520
how you can listen to that in your car.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:25.490
Well, unfortunately,
if you want to start one of those,

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:26.360
you need a satellite.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:28.570
Now there may be some channels available,
but there's a limited

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:30.420
number of channels on those,
a few hundred at most.

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.720
And basically,
that's pretty much taken at the moment,

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:35.120
so that's hard to do.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:37.890
So there's pirate radio,
and I don't know, you know,

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:40.450
if you've heard about people
putting ships out at sea off the

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:43.250
coast of California and New York,
and they broadcast, you know,

00:08:43.250 --> 00:08:46.280
out on international waters,
and you can hear the station, and, well,

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:49.880
you know, it's sort of dangerous, and,
well, it's all sort of illegal as well.

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:53.000
We actually, a few years ago at the
broadcaster show in Las Vegas,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.170
there was a group of pirate broadcasters,
and they met in a church,

00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:59.670
so they were granted asylum,
so they couldn't be arrested by the FCC.

00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:03.500
So, that's, you know, not too much fun.

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:05.060
That might be an exciting
life for some people,

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:05.700
but, you know, if you're a pirate,
you're going to have to do a lot of work.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:07.810
If you want to start something
and have a business and

00:09:07.810 --> 00:09:09.920
something you can enjoy doing,
you don't want to be on

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:12.510
the run from the police,
right, or the FCC for that matter.

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:15.430
So, to address that,
the FCC decided to put out

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:18.630
a regulation that said,
well, you can do low-power

00:09:18.630 --> 00:09:21.760
FM stations in cities,
because that won't interfere

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:23.840
with other big stations.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:26.080
Well, of course, the large broadcasters
have blocked all that,

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.030
because they say, no,
it's going to interfere with us,

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:29.370
and plus, it's also competition.

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:31.470
So,
that's what you would expect them to do.

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:33.130
So, that's, you know,
there's only a few hundred of

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:35.680
them that have been on the air,
and there's about, let's see, what is it?

00:09:35.770 --> 00:09:38.240
Say, there are 30,000 inquiries
about doing this.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:39.990
So, obviously,
there's a demand for radio.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.740
So, finally, we come to internet radio.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:45.190
So,
instead of using electromagnetic waves,

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:46.690
we're using the internet.

00:09:46.700 --> 00:09:50.820
So, that's another electronic means,
as we talked about earlier, to transmit.

00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:55.390
And, well,
it's a lower startup cost to do this.

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:57.820
So, really, you could just get some
computers and some bandwidth.

00:09:57.820 --> 00:10:00.160
If you're at a college,
you might already have bandwidth.

00:10:00.160 --> 00:10:03.280
You can rent machines, you know,
through ISPs.

00:10:03.410 --> 00:10:06.560
There are services that will give
you a... a stream where you can have

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:07.740
some number of people listening.

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:09.890
And, you know,
it's very easy to go out and

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.410
reach a worldwide audience.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:14.470
You can pretty much, you know,
hear things all over the

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:17.440
world without having to,
you know, with radio,

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:20.190
you'd have to wait for the ionosphere
to bounce the signal to you,

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:20.680
right?

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:22.340
Or, you know,
or get something on a satellite.

00:10:22.340 --> 00:10:24.400
Well, with this, you can pretty much just
do this from any computer,

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.140
and it doesn't cost you,
the person running the station,

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:29.560
anymore to reach that person
on the other side of the world,

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:32.550
in Australia, we'll say,
then it would be to just be local.

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:35.600
So, it's a pretty wide reach.

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:39.580
So, the other thing now, well,
radio frequency, we talked about,

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:40.680
is a limited spectrum.

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:43.740
Well, there really isn't a
limit to the spectrum.

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:45.700
It's really just if there's
enough IP addresses.

00:10:45.780 --> 00:10:46.740
How many IP addresses are there?

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:47.720
There could be that many stations.

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:51.740
So, it's really a lot more
things that could be done.

00:10:51.740 --> 00:10:54.400
And, we talked about it's the
same cost to reach people.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:57.740
And, one of the cool things about
internet radio is you can enhance it.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:59.740
You can have text
annotation along with that.

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:00.740
You can have images.

00:11:00.740 --> 00:11:01.740
You can have it as part of a webpage.

00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:03.620
And, you can do things that
people can have feedback.

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:07.740
So, it's... It's... You know,
it's a pretty powerful medium.

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:11.740
And, a lot of people that we work with,
they're trying to reach a very narrowly

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:15.740
focused audience of just one type of,
you know, of music.

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:18.510
And, you get a lot more in-depth
and interesting things that

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:20.740
way than you do with just,
you know,

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:23.740
kind of the commercial radio station that
has to appeal to everybody in the town.

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:26.740
So, they do...they choose
a very broad spectrum.

00:11:26.810 --> 00:11:30.270
So, and you can also... One of the things
you can get from internet radio that

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:34.630
you can't get from... How many of
you have ever gotten a ratings book

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:37.700
where they ask you to fill this out
and say what stations you listen to?

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:38.740
Right?

00:11:38.740 --> 00:11:38.740
Okay.

00:11:38.740 --> 00:11:41.740
So, that's... What they do is
they do statistical sampling.

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:43.740
So, they get, you know,
100 people in an area.

00:11:43.740 --> 00:11:45.740
And then,
they base that...the population on that.

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:47.300
And, they say, "Well,
this is how many people are listening

00:11:47.300 --> 00:11:49.740
to station X." With internet radio,
you can track very precisely

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:51.740
exactly how many people are
listening to your station.

00:11:51.740 --> 00:11:55.740
And, you know, if you want to know where
they're coming from.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:03.700
So, right now there are
about 12,000 stations,

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:06.330
traditional radio stations in the US.

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:12.490
and it took them about 80
years to get to that point.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:12.820
Excuse me.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:14.570
And Internet radio, well,
less than 10 years.

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:16.880
The first stations came
on the air about 1994.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:18.200
We're about 10 years out from that.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:21.320
And there's about 30,000 worldwide
and the number is growing.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:23.060
It's a little hard to
find the total number,

00:12:23.060 --> 00:12:25.340
but that seems to be a pretty
good approximation if you add

00:12:25.340 --> 00:12:28.180
together all the different
services and people broadcasting.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:30.090
So that's pretty phenomenal growth.

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:32.520
So, you know, for now,
let's go back a little bit and

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.090
think about traditional radio.

00:12:34.090 --> 00:12:36.450
It took it a very long time
for that technology to get,

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:38.220
you know, embedded and mature.

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:41.700
And Internet radio,
the curve has just been a huge spike.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:43.550
So this is kind of explosive growth.

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:46.900
Well, not only are the number
of stations are growing,

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.880
but the number of listeners are
growing by about 25% per year.

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:52.830
So how many of you have ever
tried to listen to the FM inside

00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:55.970
an office cubicle and all you get
is you get the noise from the,

00:12:55.970 --> 00:12:58.690
you know, the fluorescent lights or
you can't even get a signal?

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:00.150
So a lot of people listen at work.

00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:02.660
That's one of the biggest
audiences for Internet radio.

00:13:02.660 --> 00:13:06.240
And you get other things, you know,
people promoting their

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:10.460
product or services,
looking for a particular service.

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:13.230
A lot of stations are things
that are promoting something,

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:13.640
right?

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:18.670
And, you know, last night I was--how
many--anybody from Boston here?

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:21.430
I was listening to the
Red Sox game last night,

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:25.360
sorry, over the Internet radio,
which was terrific to do,

