we'll look a little bit at that later on.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:31.290
We'll go do a demo at the
end of the presentation here.

00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:33.490
So, running costs.

00:14:33.870 --> 00:14:35.570
Well,
if you're a traditional radio station,

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:38.690
you need power to power your transmitter,
and you could have some, you know,

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:40.380
large power bill, electricity bill.

00:14:40.380 --> 00:14:40.470
You could have some, you know,
large power bill,

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:40.660
electricity bill every month.

00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:40.710
You could have some, you know,
large power bill every month.

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:44.790
Well, with internet radio, the cost is,
or there are some costs of bandwidth,

00:14:44.790 --> 00:14:48.450
and that's basically for each person
that's listening to your stream,

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:50.970
you have to send those bits, however,
you know,

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:55.200
however many you need to have that person
be able to hear the audio to each person.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:58.400
There are a couple of ways to do this
that we'll talk about a little bit later,

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:00.850
but mainly, you know,
you have to pay for that bandwidth,

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:04.300
and that's one of your running costs,
and the more people listen, it scales up.

00:15:04.380 --> 00:15:06.220
There are,
depending on what kind of deals

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:08.330
you can get for bandwidth,
there are some economies

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:09.720
of scale to some extent.

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:12.020
Like, you may... You may be able to get,
you know,

00:15:12.070 --> 00:15:15.580
a bucket to start out with that gives
you pretty much your normal listenership,

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:17.340
and then if you go over that,
you pay more,

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:18.960
so you can predict what the costs are.

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:23.600
Well, so the other part is royalties,
and this is kind of the contentious part

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:28.410
that's evolved over the last few years,
and there are two types of royalties.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:31.290
So, they're actually the new royalties
that apply to internet radio,

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:33.820
which do not apply to broadcast,
are performance royalties,

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:37.500
and that's all done through the RIA,
and there's a group called SoundExchange.

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.080
We're going to be
talking a lot about this,

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:39.840
just so you know.

00:15:40.410 --> 00:15:43.900
And there's also composition royalties,
which traditional radio pays,

00:15:44.030 --> 00:15:47.380
and that's pretty much, you know,
a percentage of your revenue,

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:50.620
and it's a fairly low number,
and that goes to the composer

00:15:50.620 --> 00:15:53.840
and to the lyricist for the song,
and that's been done, you know,

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:54.350
for years.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:56.770
And so,
they're also... There are reporting

00:15:56.870 --> 00:15:59.970
requirements for both traditional
radio and for internet radio,

00:15:59.970 --> 00:16:02.560
and the internet radio ones
are a little more detailed,

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:06.670
and... But computers help
you solve some of that.

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:09.760
So let's talk about our setup costs.

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:10.600
So your computer.

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:12.600
Now we talked about the
client server model,

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:13.820
the transmitter on the high hill.

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:16.110
So kind of the equivalent
of Mount Sutro out here in

00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:19.400
San Francisco is an ISP that's
connected to the Internet backbone.

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:22.530
So you can locate your server there
and then do your remote broadcast

00:16:22.650 --> 00:16:24.150
from wherever you need to be.

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:25.720
That would be your studio.

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.970
So that server takes
connections from your listeners,

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:31.620
we talked about,
and sends some bandwidth to them.

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:33.620
And you can also track
that when they come in.

00:16:33.620 --> 00:16:34.620
You'll know who they are.

00:16:34.790 --> 00:16:37.620
And you have some kind of
encoding client or control client.

00:16:37.620 --> 00:16:40.940
We'll talk a little bit later on about
the different models that are typically

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:42.800
used for doing Internet broadcast.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:47.610
And that can send a stream to a server,
that control client,

00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:50.600
or it can just control what's
going on in the server.

00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:57.580
So bandwidth-- so basically,
the way bandwidth works out

00:16:57.580 --> 00:17:00.950
is the more bandwidth you use,
the better quality your sound is.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:02.070
And that's probably pretty obvious.

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:04.740
But with new codecs,
you can actually keep

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:06.650
lowering that amount down,
so you can actually get

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:09.460
more listeners from the same
amount of internet bandwidth.

00:17:09.510 --> 00:17:12.480
And the AAC codec-- we're going
to listen to some samples of that

00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:14.480
later on-- is pretty terrific.

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:16.060
And there's better stuff coming along.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:18.270
It's really kind of a moving thing.

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.720
The technology is getting better
and the sound is getting better.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:23.710
And the ability of people to
listen at their homes-- a lot

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:27.980
of people have broadband now--
that's gotten better as well.

00:17:28.450 --> 00:17:30.930
I talked a little bit earlier
about saying there are a

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:32.210
couple different kinds.

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.070
A unicast connection to a server
is you're sending the same

00:17:35.070 --> 00:17:36.500
bits to each person directly.

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:39.400
Multicast is a pretty cool concept,
but unfortunately,

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:41.440
it doesn't really get used in practice.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:44.830
And that is you let the Internet routers
decide who needs the stream.

00:17:44.870 --> 00:17:46.840
So only one copy goes into your network.

00:17:46.950 --> 00:17:50.100
So if there's 1,000 people
inside your network listening

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:52.810
to this network segment,
listening to your station,

00:17:52.810 --> 00:17:54.750
there's only one copy of that going in.

00:17:54.750 --> 00:17:56.810
So that minimizes cost.

00:17:56.950 --> 00:18:00.600
The problem is most of the Internet is
not really set up for that.

00:18:00.600 --> 00:18:03.520
What happens is multicast
gets thrown out by routers.

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:08.290
So multicast is very close to what
it's like to do traditional radio where

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:13.580
you're just sending one signal out and
everybody listens to the same thing.

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:21.350
OK, so now we'll get into
the interesting part,

00:18:21.350 --> 00:18:22.240
the royalties.

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:24.480
So I talked about composition royalties.

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:27.470
And those are, there's a group, BMI,
ASCAP, and CSAC.

00:18:27.480 --> 00:18:30.240
There's also something
called the Harry Fox Agency.

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:34.080
And basically you're paying, as I said,
you're paying for the composition

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:35.930
and you're paying for the lyricist.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.340
And that gets split up
by this organization.

00:18:38.360 --> 00:18:40.560
And it's based on a
percentage of revenue.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.350
And I think I have an URL down here.

00:18:42.350 --> 00:18:44.610
If not,
it's on the end of the presentation that

00:18:44.940 --> 00:18:48.880
you can go there and there's a calculator
and you can punch in the numbers.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:51.930
Based on how much revenue you
have and they give you a number.

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:53.180
And it's a fairly reasonable thing.

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:57.270
And all Internet broadcasters have
paid that back to when they started,

00:18:57.270 --> 00:18:58.170
pretty much.

00:18:58.260 --> 00:19:01.200
So the interesting royalties
are the performance royalties.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:04.290
So when the DMCA came
out back in the late 90s,

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:08.280
there's a provision in the law
that said you cannot stop someone

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:11.040
from broadcasting on the Internet.

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:12.350
There's a compulsory license.

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:15.680
You can guarantee you're not breaking
the law by broadcasting on the Internet.

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:17.400
However, you have to pay a royalty.

00:19:18.340 --> 00:19:22.100
And this ended up turning
into a performance royalty,

00:19:22.100 --> 00:19:28.510
which they've modified now to say you
can be charged either for how many people

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:29.640
are listening to a particular song.

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:30.920
This is for streaming music.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:35.530
And how many people are listening at a
particular time to when that song played.

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:39.260
Or you can just count the
amount of listening hours.

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:40.390
And they have a number.

00:19:40.390 --> 00:19:43.460
They say, well,
you played 12 or 14 songs in that hour.

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:45.390
And we'll give you a value based on that.

00:19:45.450 --> 00:19:47.780
And that's collected by a group.

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:49.610
But a new organization
called Sound Exchange,

00:19:49.770 --> 00:19:50.710
and I have an URL for that.

00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:52.540
You can check that out.

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:55.020
And there's all the real
details of that as well.

00:19:55.020 --> 00:19:58.660
So once again,
traditional broadcasters are

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:01.730
paying the composition royalties.

00:20:01.730 --> 00:20:04.700
And that's based on a few percent.

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:06.960
And there's a minimum of about $264.

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:08.090
And there's the URL.

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:08.530
Okay.

00:20:08.600 --> 00:20:09.260
There we go.

00:20:09.260 --> 00:20:10.990
That's the URL at askcap.com.

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:12.320
You can find all that.

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:13.450
Okay.

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:16.500
So, as I've mentioned,
the performance royalties

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:17.880
are very contentious.

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:20.310
I mean, it was really,
you may have seen stories about this

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:22.340
is going to kill Internet radio,
it's going to shut down.

00:20:22.340 --> 00:20:25.990
A lot of people pulled their streams
off the air and there was a lot of,

00:20:26.130 --> 00:20:29.240
you know, fear and panic and it
really made a lot of news.

00:20:29.240 --> 00:20:33.220
And that was because
this was a new thing.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:35.660
And especially for the traditional
broadcasters who were putting

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:37.680
a stream on the Internet,
they're not used to paying

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:38.800
performance royalties.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:41.740
They say, you know,
we provide a promotional value.

00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:45.530
So it was deemed that radio, you know,
had a perceived promotional

00:20:45.610 --> 00:20:46.820
value back in the 20s.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:50.330
And so that's helping the record
industry to promote their music.

00:20:50.390 --> 00:20:54.020
So because I think of,
because of the reasoning for it was

00:20:54.020 --> 00:20:56.620
because of the fragmented nature
of a lot of Internet stations,

00:20:56.620 --> 00:20:57.890
it's just a small audience.

00:20:57.970 --> 00:20:59.750
It's not, you know,
the more general thing

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:00.950
that commercial radio does.

00:21:01.070 --> 00:21:03.320
So they were able to,
they kind of negotiated it out so

00:21:03.320 --> 00:21:05.340
they had to pay performance royalties.

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:10.820
Well, so the political turmoil lasted for
about two years and Congress got involved

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:13.680
and there was a settlement act for a
lot of people that were broadcasting.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:16.690
At that time,
we're able to get in and get something

00:21:16.690 --> 00:21:18.880
that allowed them to stay in business.

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:24.770
So, and as I said,
this all goes back to the DMCA.

00:21:24.770 --> 00:21:28.300
And that was,
it was intended to address the rights

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:30.740
holder concerns in digital media.

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:32.560
And, you know,
you can imagine if you were in a

00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:35.470
business and you owned something and
suddenly people were able to get it,

00:21:35.610 --> 00:21:37.720
you know, for free,
you'd be nervous about it.

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:39.640
And if you're someone that
was already doing this,

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:42.140
you know, well,
then you'd want to keep doing it, right?

00:21:42.140 --> 00:21:44.260
Why should I pay for something
I haven't paid for before?

00:21:44.260 --> 00:21:45.100
Why do I want more costs?

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:49.560
So the players in all this are the RAA,
which I'm sure you've heard of.

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:52.580
