00:32:37.990 --> 00:32:41.180
So we talked about encoding briefly,
and really you get a trade-off.

00:32:41.180 --> 00:32:44.800
If you send more data to your listeners,
you get better quality,

00:32:44.820 --> 00:32:45.990
but it costs you more.

00:32:46.020 --> 00:32:51.060
We talked about the client-server model,
and we're talking about QuickTime here,

00:32:51.060 --> 00:32:53.220
right, because you're at WWDC.

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:55.840
So we use something called
the Realtime Protocol,

00:32:55.840 --> 00:32:58.340
which is an Internet standard
for streaming,

00:32:58.340 --> 00:33:02.440
and each QuickTime file contains in
it something called a hint track,

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:06.640
which tells a server how to go about
building the Realtime Protocol packets

00:33:06.870 --> 00:33:08.570
that need to be sent to a listener.

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:11.900
And we standardize an
MPEG-4 AAC just because,

00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:15.690
you know, it's pretty cool,
and it sounds great.

00:33:15.720 --> 00:33:18.360
And also, we're going to look at
some broadcasting models.

00:33:20.420 --> 00:33:21.840
We're doing this, so we'll say,
what is encoding?

00:33:21.840 --> 00:33:23.480
Well,
your source material could be anything.

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:26.800
It could be a CD,
it could be an MP3 that's high quality,

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:31.490
and you basically perform math on
this with some software that says,

00:33:31.540 --> 00:33:33.280
if I take out,
how much data can I take out

00:33:33.280 --> 00:33:34.560
and it still sounds good?

00:33:34.560 --> 00:33:37.250
So you can do that and
minimize the amount of data

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:40.460
