yet keep the quality.

00:33:40.460 --> 00:33:42.790
And as I said,
it's a very subjective thing,

00:33:42.790 --> 00:33:45.590
and it's really a trade-off
of how much you want to use,

00:33:45.590 --> 00:33:48.300
of bandwidth you want to use
and how much you want to pay

00:33:48.340 --> 00:33:50.060
as to how good the quality is.

00:33:50.400 --> 00:33:53.930
And, you know,
it's a very personal thing.

00:33:53.930 --> 00:33:58.760
So obviously, higher data rates,
higher quality and higher cost,

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:02.980
lower data rate, you know, basically,
it can sound okay,

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:05.180
but it's reduced quality.

00:34:05.180 --> 00:34:08.290
For example, like the baseball game I was
listening to last night was sent

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:10.690
at about 10 kilobits a second,
and it's just voice,

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:13.250
so it really sounded like kind
of a bad telephone connection,

00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:14.760
but I can understand all of it.

00:34:14.860 --> 00:34:17.960
But if you're doing Tchaikovsky, well,
you might want something that's

00:34:17.960 --> 00:34:19.540
stereo and a much better quality.

00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:23.210
So you might want to be able to have
different encodings for different types.

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:26.280
So there's some other
trade-offs you can do.

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:30.150
Stereo is great,
but you can get as good a quality at

00:34:30.150 --> 00:34:31.830
less data rate by just choosing mono.

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:37.730
So we'll talk a little
bit about MPEG-4 AAC.

00:34:37.730 --> 00:34:40.500
And this is done by Dolby Labs,
and this is included in QuickTime.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:44.240
And it's currently kind of the
state of the art for streaming.

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:48.820
And this is really,
it's based on standards.

00:34:48.820 --> 00:34:51.340
So if you and I wanted to go
out and build our own codec,

00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:54.280
we could go get a copy of the
standard and sit down and write some

00:34:54.380 --> 00:34:57.710
code and come up with something that
put out the same format as MPEG-4,

00:34:57.720 --> 00:34:59.120
and it sounds better.

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:02.840
And we could have an MPEG-4 codec,
and that's exactly what's happening.

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:06.610
So there are codecs that are on the
way that I'm sure that QuickTime will

00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:10.380
adopt as time goes by that sound
even better at lower data rates.

00:35:10.420 --> 00:35:14.180
But once you're in the standard,
it's guaranteed to be backward

00:35:14.250 --> 00:35:17.450
compatible and forward,
which is one of the great

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:19.300
things about standards.

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:21.410
And also,
standards mean that as new devices

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:24.380
come up that support the standard,
they're going to be able to

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:25.830
play your audio natively.

00:35:25.830 --> 00:35:29.110
You don't have to do anything
special to make all that happen.

00:35:29.110 --> 00:35:32.390
And there are actually
no royalties as well.

