00:36:40.010 --> 00:36:43.080
So let's talk a little bit more in
depth about the client server model.

00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:45.610
So as I said, listeners on the
Internet are your clients.

00:36:45.670 --> 00:36:48.970
It's very similar to traditional radio
where you've got the transmitter in the

00:36:49.020 --> 00:36:53.820
high hill and people listening in their
car in their home to a radio station.

00:36:53.820 --> 00:36:55.480
Well,
if you're listening on your computer,

00:36:55.560 --> 00:36:56.610
it's a very similar thing.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:00.710
So the difference with Internet radio,
of course, is we mentioned that there

00:37:00.730 --> 00:37:02.680
can be two-way communication.

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:04.420
So I can get some
information back from you.

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:05.800
You can send me an email.

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:07.070
We can do a chat, etc.

00:37:07.130 --> 00:37:13.600
And there's a lot of things that are,
you know, that's a very interesting thing

00:37:13.600 --> 00:37:16.640
that traditional radio can't do.

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:20.420
So in most cases, as we said,
we talked about multicasts and unicasts.

00:37:20.490 --> 00:37:22.660
There's a stream sent to every listener.

00:37:22.660 --> 00:37:25.060
So that's different
from traditional radio,

00:37:25.060 --> 00:37:26.180
but it's there.

00:37:26.180 --> 00:37:27.640
So let's talk a little bit about that.

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:50.550
The real-time protocol is the
way that the data that's in the

00:37:50.740 --> 00:37:55.030
stream is broken up into small
pieces and sent to the player.

00:37:55.030 --> 00:37:59.250
And it's designed so if you're
ever driving in your car and you're

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:02.330
listening to FM and you go under a
bridge and FM drops out for a second,

00:38:02.450 --> 00:38:05.960
a real-time protocol is designed to
make that possible with computers.

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:08.710
If there's some disruption in
the stream for some reason,

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:10.020
it won't just fall over.

00:38:10.020 --> 00:38:13.560
It knows that it can throw some
data away and so it can be lossy.

00:38:13.620 --> 00:38:17.260
So it's designed to kind of
exist in harsh environments.

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:20.000
and you can still get
a pretty good stream.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:24.700
And of course all the packets
have numbers and so they're

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:25.880
all sent from the server.

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:29.450
They may arrive in any order at
the player and the player decides

00:38:29.990 --> 00:38:32.300
how to put them back together
based on their sequence number and

00:38:32.300 --> 00:38:34.770
when to play them based on there's
a time stamp in each packet.

00:38:37.090 --> 00:38:40.810
So, there's also something called the
Real Time Control Protocol which

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:44.500
basically it tells the player,
this is more important

00:38:44.500 --> 00:38:47.050
if you're doing video,
but it tells the player basically,

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:51.000
you know, this video frame is at the same
time as this audio so that you

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:52.970
can sync lip sync and all that.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:57.190
But there are actually also reports sent
back from the player to your server which

00:38:57.350 --> 00:38:59.390
talk about the quality of the service.

00:38:59.390 --> 00:39:01.990
So your server can
automatically adjust itself.

00:39:02.080 --> 00:39:04.500
So this guy's having a loss,
I'll send him some repeat packets

00:39:04.520 --> 00:39:08.460
and there's kind of a you know,
there's only a certain point of

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:10.860
loss that you can go to before,
you know, things fall over.

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:13.850
But if there's just a little
bit under say 10 or 20 percent,

00:39:13.850 --> 00:39:16.060
you can actually compensate a bit and,
you know,

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:19.520
and get a still keep a good quality
stream by sending a little extra data.

00:39:27.600 --> 00:39:28.710
This is the control protocol.

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:31.550
So when you're in your
QuickTime player and you hit play

00:39:31.630 --> 00:39:34.990
and pause buttons or open a stream,
you're sending RTSP commands to

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:36.820
a server which say just that.

00:39:36.940 --> 00:39:39.270
I'd like to listen to the stream,
set it up.

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:41.440
You know, I want to play or pause.

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:46.080
If it's a file you listen to the stream,
you can actually move around randomly.

00:39:46.080 --> 00:39:48.310
You can't do that in a live
stream because obviously,

00:39:48.310 --> 00:39:49.720
you know, it's live, right?

00:39:49.810 --> 00:39:51.190
So you're hearing what's in the now.

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:54.350
It'll also tear down the connections
so the server knows if you've

00:39:54.390 --> 00:39:57.920
disconnected from the server that it
shouldn't be sending you those packets.

00:39:57.980 --> 00:40:00.500
It can use that bandwidth
for somebody else,

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:02.990
and that's all done under the covers.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:08.800
So you can take a player,
and you can encapsulate that, you know,

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:09.860
inside.

00:40:09.860 --> 00:40:12.070
You can have a stub movie that
actually just has information

00:40:12.130 --> 00:40:14.840
about what the stream is,
and you can put that inside a web

00:40:14.840 --> 00:40:17.740
page or you can mail that to somebody,
you know,

00:40:17.740 --> 00:40:20.840
or you can have your web page launch
an external player so they can be

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:25.200
scrolling through different pages as
they're listening to their radio stream

00:40:25.200 --> 00:40:28.040
so there's a lot of detail to that.

00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:30.590
I won't go into a lot of
that just because that's some

00:40:30.590 --> 00:40:34.840
things that are going on in,
you know, other sessions.

00:40:34.900 --> 00:40:37.460
I'm sure they've covered
that in a lot of detail.

00:40:37.460 --> 00:40:40.030
So let me talk a little bit
about broadcasting models.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:41.310
So how is Internet radio done?

00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:43.410
So let's kind of look at,
this is more of a

00:40:43.410 --> 00:40:46.740
traditional broadcaster,
and, you know, they've got a studio.

00:40:46.740 --> 00:40:50.320
So they've maybe got a radio automation
system that just puts out audio,

00:40:50.350 --> 00:40:50.860
right?

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:53.320
So they've got a hard drive somewhere,
or they've got some CDs,

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:55.050
or there's some places
they still do tapes,

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:55.180
right?

00:40:55.180 --> 00:40:58.300
And they put that through a mixer,
and there's a microphone, et cetera.

00:40:58.300 --> 00:41:03.480
And at some point, that comes out,
and it'll go maybe to a, you know,

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:05.740
obviously it goes to a
transmitter up on the high hill,

00:41:05.740 --> 00:41:10.150
the real, you know, RF-based broadcast,
but it goes into a compressor,

00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:13.860
and that compressor sends either
over public Internet or sometimes

00:41:13.860 --> 00:41:16.040
they just use an ISDN line so
they have guaranteed bandwidth,

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:20.180
and they send that off to an encoder
or they send the encoded data,

00:41:20.180 --> 00:41:21.480
you know, from the station.

00:41:21.480 --> 00:41:23.660
It's really a choice of the
people putting it together,

00:41:23.660 --> 00:41:25.130
and then that goes to a server.

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:26.200
So.

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:30.140
The good part about this
is it's pretty simple.

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:31.960
Well,
the bad part of it is you don't actually,

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:34.040
other than, you might be able to,
you can track the number

00:41:34.040 --> 00:41:36.300
of hours people listen to,
but you don't really know,

00:41:36.300 --> 00:41:39.270
you have to go correlate your logs to
that if you want to do performances.

00:41:39.360 --> 00:41:44.630
You really don't have that correlation
of who listened to what was played.

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:49.660
Okay, so another typical thing
is an MP3 hosting service.

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:53.330
So you upload some files manually
and you build a fixed playlist,

00:41:53.400 --> 00:41:56.640
and that fixed playlist runs,
and it can be very long, you know,

00:41:56.640 --> 00:42:00.520
and it can do some things randomly,
but it pretty much just repeats,

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:03.800
and you have to go and manually go
change that to get that to be different.

00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:07.800
And once again,
you could get some information on that,

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:10.870
on who's listening and all that,
but that has to be built

00:42:10.870 --> 00:42:11.700
into that software.

00:42:11.700 --> 00:42:12.900
Typically those are very simple.

00:42:12.930 --> 00:42:17.890
They're just really just
sending out a stream.

00:42:17.890 --> 00:42:17.890
They're not doing all the logging.

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:20.510
So we can talk about
Internet radio automation,

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:22.160
which is what I do.

00:42:22.160 --> 00:42:25.160
And in this case,
there's a control client that

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:28.080
actually controls the server remotely
from anywhere you are in the world.

00:42:28.080 --> 00:42:30.900
So really,
your server just does what it's told,

00:42:30.900 --> 00:42:33.480
and the server has a lot of intelligence.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:36.100
So it can do,
we talked about the broadcast complement,

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:39.420
there's a set of rules you have to do,
or maybe you want certain broadcasts

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:40.810
to go on at certain times.

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:43.490
The automation system can make
your station sound very fresh.

00:42:43.490 --> 00:42:46.780
And at the same time,
if you want to broadcast live,

00:42:46.990 --> 00:42:47.880
you can now cut in.

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:50.740
And just send that live
stream to that ISP,

00:42:50.740 --> 00:42:54.290
so avoiding having to
have a stream that's,

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:56.910
if there's some disruption in that,
if you're not broadcasting live,

00:42:56.910 --> 00:42:58.450
your station's going to stay on the air.

00:42:58.450 --> 00:43:01.790
And of course, that server is up on the
high hill at the ISP,

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:04.890
and you've got your
listeners listening to that.

00:43:05.130 --> 00:43:08.350
And that server can now
keep track of all the logs,

00:43:08.460 --> 00:43:12.520
it can keep track of who's
connecting and who's listening,

00:43:12.540 --> 00:43:15.990
and allows you to go off
and build your reports.

00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:18.280
So.

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:18.340
Bye.

00:43:20.660 --> 00:43:25.340
Basically, with an automation system,
you can encode the clips ahead of time

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:28.300
and put them actually physically on
the server so they don't have to be

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:30.260
streaming from the client all the time.

00:43:30.260 --> 00:43:33.760
They can just sit on the server
and run when they need to,

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.440
and you can let that run autonomously.

00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:40.520
So you could have people on the air that
are just looking at what's playing now,

00:43:40.520 --> 00:43:43.830
and they know what they can talk about,
or you can have them pre-recorded.

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:48.070
There's a number of concepts in radio
that are built in automation systems.

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:50.200
At the same time,
your program director could

00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:51.540
be choosing what's played.

00:43:51.740 --> 00:43:54.150
You can have people doing
commercials that track that,

00:43:54.180 --> 00:43:56.640
and that's called traffic
in traditional radio.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:44:00.240
They could be doing that offline and
programming the station ahead of time,

00:44:00.330 --> 00:44:02.190
and it all works very seamlessly.

00:44:02.310 --> 00:44:04.200
At the same time,
that could be done from anywhere,

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:07.200
so those people don't really even have
to be in the same physical building.

00:44:07.220 --> 00:44:10.820
They could be at a live remote somewhere,
they could be in their home,

00:44:10.820 --> 00:44:11.890
in their office.

00:44:11.890 --> 00:44:15.540
You can pretty much do a station and have
a lot of different people involved in it,

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:21.070
and not need a lot of bricks
and mortar to go and do that.

00:44:21.390 --> 00:44:24.760
So I talked a lot about
doing dynamic playlists.

00:44:24.780 --> 00:44:28.780
Basically, if you use rotation rules,
you can come up with something

00:44:28.780 --> 00:44:31.150
that sounds very fresh,
and you're not doing anything

00:44:31.150 --> 00:44:33.580
to do that because you know
it's going to be randomized.

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:37.570
You'll be following the law of
what you have to play to broadcast,

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:41.060
and you can have that set up
with a month's worth of music,

00:44:41.060 --> 00:44:44.940
and it'll play without you
having to go to see the station.

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:48.260
So a lot of stations do
something called voice tracking,

00:44:48.370 --> 00:44:50.890
where they actually
record the live inserts.

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:53.620
If you say, hey,
it's a great sunny day and it's raining,

00:44:53.670 --> 00:44:56.150
well,
that doesn't quite work out the next day.

00:44:56.160 --> 00:44:59.770
But you can do that in the future,
and a lot of radio stations do that.

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:02.990
It allows them to create
something that sounds pretty live,

00:45:02.990 --> 00:45:05.210
but without having people sitting there.

00:45:05.410 --> 00:45:08.440
The air talent can come in and
do their show in 20 minutes,

00:45:08.440 --> 00:45:11.210
half an hour,
instead of being there all along.

00:45:11.220 --> 00:45:12.840
But you can also do live assist.

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:14.220
You can actually have
somebody doing a show,

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:16.130
and they can... be
talking over their music,

00:45:16.210 --> 00:45:19.260
or if they're doing a live broadcast,
you can have, you know,

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:20.880
material running and recorded...

00:45:22.220 --> 00:45:24.300
You know, that's appropriate,
and then they can cut in and do

00:45:24.300 --> 00:45:26.380
the live show if they're doing
a sporting event or whatever,

00:45:26.380 --> 00:45:29.420
or use the playlist to have commercials
while you're doing your sporting event.

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:37.510
And, of course, an automation system does
all the logging as well.

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:41.420
So where is everything
heading at this point?

00:45:41.430 --> 00:45:44.400
Well, the royalty situation
has really stabilized.

00:45:44.400 --> 00:45:48.190
You know, one of the problems in
the period of the early,

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:51.090
you know,
2000s was that people didn't know

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:53.060
what the rules were going to be.

00:45:53.060 --> 00:45:55.910
So that's a tough thing if you're
trying to run something where

00:45:55.910 --> 00:45:57.720
you're going to have to pay and
you don't know how much that is.

00:45:57.780 --> 00:46:00.170
Well, now it's very well known,
and now it's going to

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:01.530
evolve every two years.

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:04.780
So all of you can get
involved in this process and,

00:46:04.890 --> 00:46:07.260
you know, lobby, you know,
Congress and do things

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:09.930
to try to get things to,
you know, come down even further perhaps

00:46:10.090 --> 00:46:12.120
or make it easier to report.

00:46:12.120 --> 00:46:14.300
So it's not going to be a fixed thing.

00:46:14.300 --> 00:46:16.730
It's going to be
revisited every two years.

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:19.770
And, of course, well,
there are lots of mobile

00:46:19.770 --> 00:46:21.180
devices on the way.

00:46:21.180 --> 00:46:24.010
In a few years, you'll be able to,
your radio station will be

00:46:24.060 --> 00:46:27.170
able to stream to phones,
you know, 3G and other things

00:46:27.170 --> 00:46:28.600
that are coming along.

00:46:28.600 --> 00:46:30.060
There's other standards
for high-speed data.

00:46:30.060 --> 00:46:32.180
But the thing is radio
doesn't need that much speed.

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:33.760
You don't need the one and
a half megabits a second.

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:37.480
If you have a phone that can do that
and you're just doing a 56K stream,

00:46:37.480 --> 00:46:38.250
it's going to sound great.

